The [Gulf of Mexico basin](/Gulf_of_Mexico_basin) itself presents a roughly oval configuration, stretching approximately 810 [nautical miles](/Nautical_mile) (1,500 kilometres; 930 miles) at its widest point. Its seabed, a silent archive of geological history, is composed of layers upon layers of [sedimentary rocks](/Sedimentary_rock) and more recent, unconsolidated sediments. This vast body of water maintains a rather constrained connection to the greater [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) through the narrow [Straits of Florida](/Straits_of_Florida), situated between the [United States](/United_States) and [Cuba](/Cuba). Another vital maritime passage, the [Yucatán Channel](/Yucat%C3%A1n_Channel), links it with the vibrant [Caribbean Sea](/Caribbean_Sea), positioned between [Mexico](/Mexico) and [Cuba](/Cuba). This somewhat isolated hydrological arrangement, a consequence of its narrow oceanic gateways, accounts for the remarkably small [tidal ranges](/Tides) observed within the gulf, a minor detail that nonetheless shapes its coastal ecosystems.

Beyond its intrinsic geological and hydrological characteristics, the gulf plays an unexpectedly critical role in the atmospheric dynamics of the North American continent. Moisture, ceaselessly evaporated from its warm surface, is a primary ingredient in the complex meteorological ballet that unfolds across the [United States](/United_States). This atmospheric contribution is particularly significant, feeding the severe weather systems that frequently manifest in the infamous region known as [Tornado Alley](/Tornado_Alley).

The sheer scale of the [gulf basin](/Gulf_of_Mexico_basin) is impressive, encompassing an approximate surface area of 1.6 million square kilometres (620,000 square miles). A significant portion—nearly half, in fact—is comprised of relatively shallow [continental shelf](/Continental_shelf) waters, areas teeming with life and economic activity. The total volume of water held within this immense natural reservoir is roughly 2.4 million cubic kilometres (580 thousand cubic miles). This vast volume of water, combined with its unique geological history, has made the gulf one of the world's most crucial regions for [offshore petroleum](/Offshore_drilling) production, accounting for a substantial 14% of the total output for the [United States](/United_States). It’s a testament to humanity’s relentless pursuit of resources, even in the depths.

## Name

See also: [Gulf of Mexico naming controversy](/Gulf_of_Mexico_naming_controversy)

English nautical chart from 1700 labels the body of water "the Great Bay of Mexico"
English nautical chart dated 1775 labels "the Bay of Mexico", now glossing "Mexico" as an alternative name for New Spain
[U.S. Geological Survey](/U.S._Geological_Survey) map, February 2025

The nomenclature of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), much like the [name of Mexico](/Name_of_Mexico) itself, is intrinsically linked to the ethnonym [Mexica](/Mexica). This term refers to the [Nahuatl](/Nahuatl)-speaking people who once dominated the [Valley of Mexico](/Valley_of_Mexico), a civilization more commonly recognized by the moniker [Aztecs](/Aztecs). In their rich [Aztec religion](/Aztec_religion) and cosmological understanding, the gulf was not merely a geographical feature but a sacred domain, known as *Chalchiuhtlicueyecatl*, which translates evocatively to 'House of [Chalchiuhtlicue](/Chalchiuhtlicue)'. This name honored the deity associated with seas, rivers, and all forms of water. The Aztecs, with their profound connection to the natural world, perceived the vast expanse where sea and sky converged beyond the visible horizon as *ilhuicaatl*, meaning 'sky water', a poetic contrast to the finite, landlocked lakes and lagoons familiar to their inland empire. Meanwhile, the ancient [Maya civilization](/Maya_civilization), whose extensive maritime networks utilized the gulf as [a major trade route](/Maritime_trade_in_the_Maya_civilization), likely referred to this grand expanse of water as *nahá*, simply meaning 'great water', a pragmatic yet equally fitting description.

The early European encounters with this immense body of water were, predictably, marked by a period of geographical uncertainty and a proliferation of provisional names. Up until approximately 1530, European cartographers, though aware of its existence, often depicted the gulf without a definitive label on their maps. [Hernán Cortés](/Hern%C3%A1n_Cort%C3%A9s), the notorious conquistador, somewhat grandiosely referred to it as the "Sea of the North" ([Spanish](/Spanish_language): *Mar del Norte*) in his official dispatches, perhaps to distinguish it from the Pacific Ocean, which was often called the "Sea of the South." Other Spanish explorers, with varying degrees of accuracy and regional focus, called it the "Gulf of Florida" (*Golfo de Florida*) or even the "Gulf of Cortés" (*Golfo de Cortés*), reflecting their points of entry or perceived dominance. A 1584 map by the renowned cartographer [Abraham Ortelius](/Abraham_Ortelius) also echoed Cortés's designation, labeling it as the "Sea of the North" (*Mare de Nort*). Other ephemeral names appearing on early European maps included the "Gulf of St. Michael" ([Latin](/Latin_language): *Sinus S. Michaelis*), the "Gulf of [Yucatán](/Yucat%C3%A1n_Peninsula)" (*Golfo de Iucatan*), the "Yucatán Sea" (*Mare Iuchatanicum*), the rather ambitious "Great [Antillean](/Antilles) Gulf" (*Sinus Magnus Antillarum*), the exotic "[Cathayan](/Cathay) Sea" (*Mare Cathaynum*), or the more politically charged "Gulf of New Spain" ([Spanish](/Spanish_language): *Golfo de Nueva España*). It’s worth noting that at one historical juncture, the vast colonial territory of [New Spain](/New_Spain) effectively encircled the entire gulf, with the fabled [Spanish Main](/Spanish_Main) extending into what would eventually become modern [Mexico](/Mexico) and the southeastern [United States](/United_States), solidifying Spanish influence over the region.

The name that eventually stuck, "Gulf of Mexico" ([Spanish](/Spanish_language): *golfo de México*; [French](/French_language): *golphe du Mexique*, later *golfe du Mexique*), made its initial appearance on a world map in 1550 and was documented in a historical account two years later in 1552. As was common practice for naming large bodies of water, Europeans decided to christen the gulf after [Mexico](/Mexico), the land of the [Mexica](/Mexica) people, largely because mariners frequently had to traverse this body of water to reach that significant destination. This particular designation gradually gained prominence and has remained the most widely accepted name since the mid-17th century. During this period, it was still very much considered a Spanish sea, reflecting the dominant colonial power. French [Jesuits](/Jesuits) were observed using this name as early as 1672, indicating its growing international adoption. Even in the 18th century, Spanish admiralty charts, while acknowledging the established name, sometimes used descriptive alternatives such as "Mexican Cove" or "Mexican Sound" (*Ensenada Mexicana* or *Seno Mexicano*). It’s a historical footnote that until the [Republic of Texas](/Republic_of_Texas) asserted its independence from [Mexico](/Mexico) in 1836, [Mexico's](/Mexico) coastal boundary stretched eastward along the gulf, reaching into what is now [Louisiana](/Louisiana).

Among the diverse [languages of Mexico](/Languages_of_Mexico), the gulf is known by various names, reflecting the rich linguistic heritage of the region: *Ayollohco Mexihco* in [Nahuatl](/Nahuatl), *u golfoil México* in [Yucatec Maya](/Yucatec_Maya_language), and *golfo yu'un México* in [Tzotzil](/Tzotzil_language). While there isn't a universally enforced protocol for the general naming of [international waters](/International_waters), the name "Gulf of Mexico" holds official recognition from the [International Hydrographic Organization](/International_Hydrographic_Organization) (IHO). This body diligently works to standardize the names of international maritime features for various critical purposes, and importantly, all three nations bordering the gulf—[Cuba](/Cuba), [Mexico](/Mexico), and the [United States](/United_States)—are active member states of this organization.

However, the tranquility of established naming conventions was recently disturbed. In [a January 2025 executive order](/Executive_Order_14172), [United States](/United_States) president [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump) directed [federal agencies](/List_of_federal_agencies_in_the_United_States) to adopt the rather nationalistic name "Gulf of America" for the waters bounded by the [U.S. continental shelf](/Continental_shelf_of_the_United_States). While the executive order initially specified an area of the [U.S. continental shelf](/Continental_shelf_of_the_United_States) "extending to the seaward boundary with Mexico and Cuba," the [Geographic Names Information System](/Geographic_Names_Information_System) (GNIS) and the [GEOnet Names Server](/GEOnet_Names_Server) (GNS) were subsequently modified to explicitly refer to the gulf as a whole, without distinguishing territorial waters or the continental shelf. Predictably, some major online map platforms and several [U.S.](/United_States)-based media outlets, ever eager to comply, voluntarily adopted this change. This move, however, did not go unnoticed, sparking significant controversy and outright objections from figures such as Mexican president [Claudia Sheinbaum](/Claudia_Sheinbaum) and others, who rightly pointed out the absurdity and unilateral nature of such a declaration regarding an international body of water. One might suggest that renaming a major international sea is a rather quaint way to assert dominance, like a child drawing a new border on a shared sandbox.

## Extent

The [International Hydrographic Organization](/International_Hydrographic_Organization) (IHO), through its authoritative publication [Limits of Oceans and Seas](/Limits_of_Oceans_and_Seas) (3rd edition, published in 1953), meticulously delineates the southeastern boundary of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) with precise geographical coordinates. This boundary is defined by a specific line that intricately connects several key points.

It begins by joining the [Cape Catoche](/Cape_Catoche) [Light](/List_of_lighthouses_in_Mexico) (located at 21°37′N 87°04′W) with the [Light](/Cabo_San_Antonio_Lighthouse) on [Cape San Antonio](/Cape_San_Antonio,_Cuba) in [Cuba](/Cuba). From this point, the line traverses the island of [Cuba](/Cuba) itself, extending to the [meridian of 83°W](/83rd_meridian_west). It then proceeds northward along this meridian until it reaches the latitude of the southernmost point of the [Dry Tortugas](/Dry_Tortugas) (24°35′N). Following this parallel, the boundary continues eastward to [Rebecca Shoal](/Rebecca_Shoal_Light) (82°35′W). Finally, it weaves through the various shoals and the intricate chain of the [Florida Keys](/Florida_Keys) until it reaches the mainland at the eastern end of [Florida Bay](/Florida_Bay). All the narrow, interconnected waters situated between the [Dry Tortugas](/Dry_Tortugas_National_Park) and the mainland are explicitly considered to be an integral part of the gulf, completing its defined geographical extent. It's a rather detailed set of instructions, as if the sea itself needed a precise set of blueprints.

## Population

The human footprint around the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) is substantial, reflecting centuries of settlement and resource utilization. Along the [Gulf Coast of the United States](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States), often referred to as the Gulf Coastal Region, reside portions of five [U.S. states](/United_States) directly bordering this massive body of water. In 2016, the combined population of this region reached an estimated 15.8 million people. This stretch of coastline is home to several major urban centers, including the sprawling metropolis of [Houston, Texas](/Houston); the culturally rich and historically significant city of [New Orleans, Louisiana](/New_Orleans); the port city of [Mobile, Alabama](/Mobile,_Alabama); and the Floridian gem of [Pensacola, Florida](/Pensacola,_Florida). These cities serve as economic hubs, cultural melting pots, and critical logistical points for the industries that thrive along the gulf.

Across the border, the six [Mexican states](/List_of_states_of_Mexico) that face the gulf collectively support an even larger population, totaling approximately 19.1 million people. This demographic concentration underscores the deep historical and cultural ties [Mexico](/Mexico) holds with the gulf, with communities relying on its resources for sustenance, trade, and livelihood.

Finally, three provinces situated in northwestern [Cuba](/Cuba), including the iconic capital city of [Havana](/Havana), directly border the gulf. These Cuban provinces collectively account for a population of roughly 3,211,000 people. While the exact length of [Cuba's](/Cuba) official gulf coastline is sometimes debated, ranging from 100 to 400 km (60–250 miles), its strategic position and the population density along its northern shores undeniably place it as a key player in the gulf's human geography. The sheer number of people living in these coastal areas highlights the immense societal and economic reliance on the gulf's health and resources, a reliance that often clashes with the environmental realities.

## Geology

The very formation of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) is a grand narrative etched in stone, a testament to the slow, inexorable forces of [plate tectonics](/Plate_tectonics) that began approximately 300 million years ago. Before the late [Triassic](/Triassic) period, a time almost unimaginably distant, the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) as we know it simply did not exist. Instead, this region was dry land, composed of ancient [continental crust](/Continental_crust)—the same crust that now underpins the [Yucatán](/Yucat%C3%A1n) Peninsula—situated firmly within the heart of the supercontinent [Pangaea](/Pangaea). This landmass was bordered to the south by a continuous, imposing mountain range. This colossal range stretched from the north-central parts of [Mexico](/Mexico), through the [Marathon Uplift](/Marathon_Uplift) in western [Texas](/Texas), across the [Ouachita Mountains](/Ouachita_Mountains) of [Oklahoma](/Oklahoma), and finally into [Alabama](/Alabama), where it merged seamlessly with the majestic [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains). This immense geological feature was the direct result of the violent collision of continental plates that ultimately assembled [Pangaea](/Pangaea). However, as interpreted by geologists Roy Van Arsdale and Randel T. Cox, this mountain range was later dramatically breached during the late [Cretaceous](/Cretaceous) period by the formation of the [Mississippi Embayment](/Mississippi_Embayment), a significant event that reshaped the continental landscape.

Ship and oil rigs in the gulf (2002)

The subsequent [rifting](/Rift) that initiated the formation of the [gulf basin](/Gulf_of_Mexico_basin) was not a random occurrence but rather a consequence of inherent zones of weakness within the colossal fabric of [Pangaea](/Pangaea). These weaknesses often corresponded to ancient [sutures](/Suture_(geology))—geological scars where the [Laurentia](/Laurentia), [South American](/South_American_Plate), and [African](/African_Plate) plates had previously collided to form the supercontinent. The rifting process unfolded in distinct phases. The first, a late [Triassic](/Triassic)–early [Jurassic](/Jurassic) phase, was characterized by the formation of deep [rift valleys](/Rift_valley) which subsequently filled with distinctive continental [red beds](/Red_beds)—sediments stained crimson by iron oxides. Following this, during the early and middle [Jurassic](/Jurassic) periods, the continental crust underwent immense stretching and thinning as the rifting intensified. This thinning process created a vast zone of transitional crust, characterized by modest and uneven thinning accompanied by significant [block faulting](/Fault_block), and a broader region of uniformly thinned transitional crust, reduced to about half the typical 40 km (25-mile) thickness of continental crust. During this critical period, the initial rifting event forged a connection to the [Pacific Ocean](/Pacific_Ocean) across central [Mexico](/Mexico), which was later followed by an eastward connection to the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean). This pivotal development allowed the nascent basin to flood, creating an enclosed [marginal sea](/Marginal_sea). As the transitional crust continued to subside, it was blanketed by the widespread deposition of the [Louann Salt](/Louann_Salt) and its associated [anhydrite](/Anhydrite) [evaporites](/Evaporite), a clear indicator of restricted water circulation and intense evaporation. By the late [Jurassic](/Jurassic), the relentless rifting had widened the basin sufficiently to progress to the point of active [seafloor spreading](/Seafloor_spreading), leading to the generation of true [oceanic crust](/Oceanic_crust). At this juncture, sufficient circulation with the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) was finally established, bringing an end to the deposition of the vast [Louann Salt](/Louann_Salt) layers. This dynamic [seafloor spreading](/Seafloor_spreading) ceased at the close of the [Jurassic](/Jurassic) period, approximately 145–150 million years ago, leaving behind a nascent, but recognizably gulf-shaped basin.

[Cantarell Field](/Cantarell_Field) (2015)

From the late [Jurassic](/Jurassic) through the early [Cretaceous](/Cretaceous), the newly formed basin entered a prolonged phase of cooling and [subsidence](/Subsidence) of the underlying crust. This subsidence was a complex interplay of crustal stretching, thermal contraction, and the immense weight of accumulating sediments. Initially, the combination of crustal stretching and cooling caused a significant tectonic subsidence of about 5–7 km (3.1–4.3 miles) in the central, thin transitional and oceanic crust. The basin expanded and deepened considerably during this time, as the rate of subsidence outpaced the rate at which sediments could fill it.

Subsequently, the sheer weight, or 'loading,' of the crust within the basin and its adjacent coastal plain by the accumulation of kilometers of sediments throughout the remainder of the [Mesozoic](/Mesozoic) and the entirety of the [Cenozoic](/Cenozoic) eras further depressed the underlying crust. This process brought it to its current impressive depth of approximately 10–20 km (6.2–12.4 miles) below sea level. During the [Cenozoic](/Cenozoic), a period characterized by relative tectonic stability along the coastal zones, thick [clastic wedges](/Clastic_wedge) prograded, steadily building out the [continental shelf](/Continental_shelf) along the northwestern and northern margins of the basin.

[Sediment](/Sediment)-laden water pours into the northern [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) from the [Atchafalaya River](/Atchafalaya_River) (2009)

To the east, the remarkably stable [Florida Platform](/Florida_Platform) remained emergent—above sea level—until the very latest [Jurassic](/Jurassic) or the dawn of [Cretaceous](/Cretaceous) time. Similarly, the [Yucatán Platform](/Yucat%C3%A1n_Platform) was largely unsubmerged until the mid-[Cretaceous](/Cretaceous). Once both platforms were finally inundated by the sea, their subsequent geological history has been primarily defined by the extensive formation of [carbonates](/Carbonate_rock) and [evaporites](/Evaporite). During the early [Cretaceous](/Cretaceous), the majority of the basin's rim was characterized by thriving carbonate platforms. Later, during the latest [Cretaceous](/Cretaceous) and early [Paleogene](/Paleogene) periods, the western flank of the gulf became involved in a significant compressive deformation event known as the [Laramide Orogeny](/Laramide_Orogeny). This powerful tectonic episode was responsible for the uplift and formation of the majestic [Sierra Madre Oriental](/Sierra_Madre_Oriental) mountain range in eastern [Mexico](/Mexico), further shaping the regional geology.

The [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) is structurally diverse, comprising 41% [continental slope](/Continental_margin), 32% [continental shelf](/Continental_shelf), and 24% [abyssal plain](/Abyssal_plain). Its deepest point, the [Sigsbee Deep](/Sigsbee_Deep), plunges to an impressive 12,467 feet (3,800 meters), a testament to the vast geological forces at play.

Geologists and oceanographers typically divide the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) into seven primary, distinct areas, each possessing unique characteristics:

*   The central [Gulf of Mexico basin](/Gulf_of_Mexico_basin), which encompasses the profoundly deep [Sigsbee Deep](/Sigsbee_Deep), a geological feature that plummets to the very floor of the basin.
*   The Northeast [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), an expansive zone stretching from a point east of the prodigious [Mississippi River Delta](/Mississippi_River_Delta) near [Biloxi, Mississippi](/Biloxi,_Mississippi), eastward to the far side of [Apalachee Bay](/Apalachee_Bay) in [Florida](/Florida).
*   The South [Florida](/Florida) [Continental Shelf](/Continental_shelf) and Slope, which follows the coastline from [Apalachee Bay](/Apalachee_Bay) down to the vital [Straits of Florida](/Straits_of_Florida), a region that includes the iconic [Florida Keys](/Florida_Keys) and the remote [Dry Tortugas](/Dry_Tortugas_National_Park).
*   The [Campeche Bank](/Campeche_Bank), an extensive, shallow platform that projects from the [Yucatán Straits](/Yucat%C3%A1n_Channel) in the east to the [Tabasco](/Tabasco)–[Campeche Basin](/Campeche_Bank) in the west, and is home to the biologically rich [Arrecife Alacran](/Scorpion_Reef) (Scorpion Reef).
*   The [Bay of Campeche](/Bay_of_Campeche), a significant [bight](/Bight_(geography)) or curving indentation of the coastline that extends from the western margin of the [Campeche Bank](/Campeche_Bank) to the offshore regions situated east of [Veracruz](/Veracruz_(city)).
*   The Western [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), a strip of water located between [Veracruz](/Veracruz_(city)) to the south and the mighty [Rio Grande](/Rio_Grande) to the north, forming a critical border region.
*   The Northwest [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), an area that spans from [Alabama](/Alabama) westward to the mouth of the [Rio Grande](/Rio_Grande), representing a significant portion of the [U.S.](/United_States) gulf coastline.

### Brine pools

Deep beneath the surface of the northern half of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), a series of truly alien environments exist: the so-called [brine pools](/Brine_pool), sometimes morbidly referred to as brine lakes. These remarkable geological features vary dramatically in size, from mere 1-meter (3 ft 3 in) puddles to vast, submerged lakes stretching an astonishing 20 kilometers (12 mi) in length. The formation of these hyper-saline pools is directly tied to the unique subsurface geology of the gulf. [Brine](/Brine) is generated wherever the regular seawater of the gulf comes into contact with the ancient [Louann Salt](/Louann_Salt), a massive [evaporite](/Evaporite) formation dating back to the [Jurassic](/Jurassic) period. This interaction occurs along geological [faults](/Fault_(geology)) or within unconsolidated sediments, allowing seawater to penetrate and dissolve the buried salt. The [Louann Salt](/Louann_Salt) itself is an immense subterranean layer, extending beneath most of the [continental shelf](/Continental_shelf) around the northern reaches of the gulf, from west of [Florida](/Florida) all the way to [Texas](/Texas). Under the immense pressure of overlying sediments, this ductile salt deforms and slowly migrates, a fascinating geological process known as [salt tectonics](/Salt_tectonics). These migrating salt masses can rise through the overlying sediments, forming towering [salt domes](/Salt_domes), or they may be extruded along the [Sigsbee Escarpment](/Sigsbee_Escarpment), a dramatic underwater cliff where the steep slope of the [continental shelf](/Continental_shelf) exposes these deeper, ancient strata.

The brines within these pools are extraordinarily concentrated, typically exceeding 200 [parts-per-thousand](/Parts-per_notation) (ppt) of salt, making them 25% or more denser than typical seawater, which averages around 35 ppt. This profound density difference creates a natural barrier, effectively preventing the denser brine from mixing with the lighter, surrounding seawater. Consequently, the brine, once formed, flows downslope along the seabed, accumulating in any available depressions or basins on the gulf floor. Adding to the complexity, [hydrocarbons](/Hydrocarbon) and [gas hydrates](/Gas_hydrate) often rise from underlying salt [diapirs](/Diapir) (piercing salt intrusions), which can cause the seafloor to dome upwards. Occasionally, the eruption of gas can be powerful enough to carve out a distinct depression in the gulf floor, often encircled by a rim, perfectly shaped for brine to collect. A prime example is the East Flower Garden Bank brine pool, nestled within a crater formed by the collapsed cap of a salt dome. This circular pool, covering a modest 500 square meters (5,400 sq ft) with a maximum depth of 25 centimeters (9.8 in), lies 70 meters (230 ft) beneath the gulf's surface. It is a harsh, [anoxic](/Anoxic_waters) environment, devoid of oxygen and rich in toxic [hydrogen sulfide](/Hydrogen_sulfide) and [methane](/Methane).

Another notable brine pool, known as GB425, is found at a depth of 600 meters (2,000 ft) and is continuously fed by an active [mud volcano](/Mud_volcano). The surface temperature of this particular pool can fluctuate wildly, from a chilly 6 °C (43 °F) to a scorching 48 °C (118 °F), averaging around 20 °C (68 °F)—significantly warmer than the normal bottom temperatures of the gulf. Nearby, the GC233 brine pool exists at a similar depth of 650 meters (2,130 ft). This pool occupies a depression atop a mound and covers approximately 190 square meters (2,000 sq ft). While GC233 receives a lower inflow of brine than GB425 and maintains a temperature about 15 °C (59 °F) cooler, both pools share striking similarities: a salinity of approximately 130 ppt, low levels of sulfides, almost no sulfates, and notably high concentrations of [hydrocarbons](/Hydrocarbon).

The [Orca Basin](/Orca_Basin), a truly colossal brine pool, is situated at an impressive depth of 2,100 meters (6,900 ft). It sprawls across an area of about 400 square kilometers (150 sq mi) and reaches a maximum depth of 350 meters (1,150 ft). Its immense size is attributed to the merger of several individual salt domes. Within this basin, salinity increases gradually over a depth of 75 meters (246 ft), eventually reaching an astounding 300 ppt at its deepest points, where dissolved oxygen levels plummet to zero, rendering it utterly inhospitable to most life forms.

Perhaps the most famously described brine pool was discovered in 2014, resting on the seafloor at a depth of 1,000 meters (3,300 ft). This particular pool, with a circumference of 30 meters (100 ft) and a depth of 4 meters (12 ft), is four to five times saltier than the surrounding seawater. The extreme conditions within this site are so severe that it can only sustain a select few specialized organisms: certain types of bacteria, hardy [mussels](/Mussel) that thrive through [symbiotic relationships](/Symbiosis) with chemosynthetic bacteria, resilient [tube worms](/Tube_worm), and particular species of [shrimp](/Shrimp). Due to its unusually high temperature of 18 °C (65 °F) compared to the frigid 4 °C (39 °F) of the ambient deep-sea water, it has been aptly, and perhaps a touch dramatically, dubbed the "Jacuzzi of Despair." One can almost hear Emma's dry commentary on such a name, "As if the despair of existence wasn't enough, it now comes with a warm, salty bath."

## Hydrology

The intricate circulation of water within and through the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) is not an isolated phenomenon but an integral and dynamic component of the larger, grander circulation patterns of the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean). Water predominantly flows into the gulf from the [Caribbean Sea](/Caribbean_Sea) through the narrow yet deep [Yucatan Channel](/Yucatan_Channel), forming the powerful [Yucatan Current](/Yucatan_Current). This influx then exits the gulf, making its way to the [North Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) via the [Florida Straits](/Florida_Straits), where it transforms into the formidable [Florida Current](/Florida_Current), which in turn feeds the even more renowned [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream). It's a continuous, oceanic conveyor belt, moving vast quantities of water across the globe.

Crucially, the movement of water through these two vital straits—the [Yucatan](/Yucatan_Channel) and [Florida](/Florida_Straits)—is largely confined to the upper layers of the ocean. This limitation is due to the maximum depths of these passages: the [Yucatan Strait](/Yucatan_Channel) plunges to only 1,800 meters (5,900 ft), while the [Florida Straits](/Florida_Straits) are even shallower, reaching a maximum depth of just 900 meters (3,000 ft). These topographical constraints mean that the deeper, colder waters of the [Atlantic](/Atlantic_Ocean) and [Caribbean](/Caribbean_Sea) do not freely exchange with the gulf's abyss.

The [Yucatan Current](/Yucatan_Current) itself is a powerful force, filling most of the [Yucatan Channel](/Yucatan_Channel) to a depth of up to 800 meters (2,600 ft), with its core flowing at an impressive maximum speed of 120 centimeters (47 in) per second. Along the coasts of [Cuba](/Cuba) and [Yucatan](/Yucat%C3%A1n) and beneath the main current, weaker countercurrents exist, adding complexity to the flow. The average [volumetric flow rate](/Volumetric_flow_rate) through the [Yucatan Channel](/Yucatan_Channel), measured between 1999 and 2013, exhibited significant variability, ranging from 15.8 to 28.1 [Sverdrups](/Sverdrup) (a unit equivalent to one million cubic meters per second, or [hectometers](/Hectometers) per second, indicating a monumental movement of water). Similarly, the [Florida Current](/Florida_Current) occupies the entirety of the [Florida Straits](/Florida_Straits) (at approximately 81°W, between the lower [Florida Keys](/Florida_Keys) and [Cuba](/Cuba)) to a depth of 800 meters (2,600 ft), with a maximum flow of 110 centimeters (43 in) per second. Its average [volumetric flow rate](/Volumetric_flow_rate) through the [Florida Straits](/Florida_Straits) was observed to be remarkably consistent, hovering between 27.2 and 27.9 [Sverdrups](/Sverdrup).

A critical feature connecting the [Yucatan Current](/Yucatan_Current) to the [Florida Current](/Florida_Current) is an [anti-cyclonic](/Cyclonic_rotation) (clockwise) loop of water, known as the [Loop Current](/Loop_Current), which exhibits considerable variability in its size and penetration. This [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) can extend significantly into the northeastern part of the gulf and may even flow over the [continental shelf](/Continental_shelf) along the western coast of the [Florida](/Florida) peninsula. Its strength rivals that of the mighty [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream), and it exerts a dominant influence over the entire gulf's circulation. As this powerful current meanders, it sheds both [anti-cyclonic](/Cyclonic_rotation) (clockwise) and [cyclonic](/Cyclonic_rotation) (anti-clockwise) rings or [eddies](/Eddy_(fluid_dynamics)) that then propagate into the western gulf. These cyclonic and anti-cyclonic [eddies](/Eddy_(fluid_dynamics)) often form in pairs, and such pairs frequently dictate the prevailing circulation patterns in the western half of the gulf. It’s a complex, swirling dance of water, perpetually reshaping the local oceanography.

The [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) itself can reach an impressive diameter of up to 300 kilometers (190 mi) and is frequently surrounded by smaller, counter-clockwise [cyclonic eddies](/Cyclonic_rotation). Large, warm-core rings, or [eddies](/Eddy_(fluid_dynamics)), are periodically shed from the main [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) at irregular intervals, detaching and wandering into the wider gulf. The dynamic presence and extent of the [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) are readily observable in satellite images, which effectively track both [sea surface temperatures](/Sea_surface_temperature) and [sea surface height](/Ocean_surface_topography) anomalies. On the eastern side of the gulf, a weaker countercurrent flows northward along the [continental slope](/Continental_margin) of the [Florida](/Florida) peninsula, completing a more localized circulation pattern. In the northeastern corner of the gulf, a subdued [cyclonic circulation](/Cyclonic_rotation) exists over the [continental shelf](/Continental_shelf). The intensity of this particular circulation is inversely proportional to how far north the [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) extends, demonstrating the interconnectedness of these oceanic phenomena.

The [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) is an essential component of the larger [North Atlantic Gyre](/North_Atlantic_Gyre), a vast system of [ocean currents](/Ocean_current) that includes the [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream), the [North Atlantic Current](/North_Atlantic_Current), the [Canary Current](/Canary_Current), and the [North Equatorial Current](/North_Equatorial_Current). The [eddies](/Eddy_(fluid_dynamics)) that detach from the [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) then spread throughout the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), influencing the circulation in almost every corner of this expansive basin. The process by which these [eddies](/Eddy_(fluid_dynamics)) are generated is highly variable and often complex, influenced in part by the degree to which the [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) has penetrated into the gulf. Intriguingly, these shed [eddies](/Eddy_(fluid_dynamics)) sometimes reattach to the main [Loop Current](/Loop_Current), creating a dynamic feedback loop. Furthermore, the smaller [eddies](/Eddy_(fluid_dynamics)) that encircle the [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) interact with it, affecting both the extent of the loop's penetration into the gulf and the size and number of [eddies](/Eddy_(fluid_dynamics)) it sheds. It's a system of constant, intricate motion, a reminder that nothing in the ocean stays still for long.

These rings or [eddies](/Eddy_(fluid_dynamics)) shed from the [Loop Current](/Loop_Current) can be formidable, reaching diameters of up to 300 kilometers (190 mi) and depths ranging from 800 to 1,000 meters (2,600 to 3,300 ft). The outer currents within these rings can achieve speeds of up to 4 knots (7.4 km/h; 4.6 mph), while the rings themselves generally drift westward at a more leisurely pace of about 0.20 knots (0.37 km/h; 0.23 mph).

It's also worth noting that the water entering the gulf from the [Caribbean Sea](/Caribbean_Sea) is not a homogenous mass. Approximately 40% of this inflow originates from the [South Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean), characterized by its warmer temperatures and lower salinity compared to the rest of the water. This distinct South Atlantic component is most discernible within the upper 100 meters (330 ft) of the left-hand and central portions of the [Florida Current](/Florida_Current). A deeper component within the current consists of [Antarctic Intermediate Water](/Antarctic_Intermediate_Water), a cold, relatively fresh water mass that has traveled vast distances. The remaining volume of water transported into the gulf is composed of various distinct masses originating from the [North Atlantic](/Atlantic_Ocean), creating a complex stratification of water types within this dynamic basin.

## History

